column62:
The Plan objectives include...
1. Maintain and improve water supply reliability;(based on the findings of this Plan, this objective means to mitigate the projected loss to water supply reliability since it may not be possible to improve beyond the historical condition)
2. Maintain groundwater levels at economically viable pumping lifts;
3. Protect the quality of groundwater and enhance where practical;
4. Maintain water supply costs at a level commensurate with the continued viability of the agricultural economy which has developed in the region;
5. Enhance monitoring activities to meet groundwater level and water quality goals;
6. Maintain and/or enhance environmental resources within and outside of the region; and
7. Enhance flood control in the region.

column61:
Major water issues include: 
Lack of adequate surface water; 
Groundwater overdraft; 
Migration of saline groundwater; 
Environmental quality of the community; 
Health of the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta; 
Supply reliability during multi-year droughts; 
Competing urban, agricultural, and environmental water demands; 
Expansion of agriculture into historically un-irrigated areas; 
Sustainability of economies dependent water supply; 
Flood protection; and 
Funding and financing.

Because the Management Area is part of a regional aquifer system, integrated regional solutions are essential to solve key regional issues while avoiding or minimizing conflict.  No one solution will fully address the underlying issues facing the area.  The solution requires an integrated mix of water management strategies. Failure to address water supply and management needs will ultimately result in severe social, economic, and environmental disruptions to the Region.

